  "prompt": "What is contingent asset and contingent liability?",
  "response": "Contingent assets and contingent liabilities are potential financial outcomes that depend on uncertain future events.\n\nContingent Asset:\n1. Definition\n- A potential asset arising from past events\n- Existence will be confirmed only by occurrence or non-occurrence of uncertain future events\n- Not recognized in financial statements\n- Disclosed in notes if probability of economic benefit is high\n\n2. Example\n- Pending lawsuit where the company expects to receive compensation\n- Insurance claim where reimbursement is probable\n- Potential tax refund under legal dispute\n\nContingent Liability:\n1. Definition\n- A potential financial obligation arising from past events\n- Existence will be confirmed by occurrence of uncertain future events\n- Recognized in financial statements if:\n   - Probability of occurrence is high\n   - Amount can be reasonably estimated\n\n2. Example\n- Pending legal lawsuit against the company\n- Product warranty claims\n- Environmental remediation obligations\n- Potential tax penalties\n\nKey Differences:\n- Contingent asset represents potential economic benefit\n- Contingent liability represents potential financial obligation\n- Both depend on uncertain future events\n- Accounting treatment differs based on probability and estimability\n\nAccounting Standard: These are typically governed by IAS 37 (International Accounting Standard) and similar local accounting standards.",
